<br>
So ... why the hell should we care what happens to criminals?<br>
<br>
At this point it's sometimes difficult to state that people have a right to live even if they're completely innocent. The world is getting more and more overcrowded, energy may soon become a scarce commodity, and we are quickly outgrowing the resources available to us.<br>
It's not at all inconcievable that this century will see laws imposed over, for instance, the number of children that a family can have.<br>
<br>
And in the midst of all this we're supposed to be concerned about the possible rehabilitation of people who harm society? About those who murder or rape people for private reasons?<br>
<br>
Why? Let's kill as many of them as we can reasonably justify and thereby make the world as a whole a better place.<br>
<br>
Yes, here and there an innocent person will probably die.<br>
So? Lots of innocent people die all the time anyway, shit happens. And from a utilitarianist outlook[1], a hardline approach to criminal punishment is almost certainly the morally right choice even if it DOES mean the occasional death of innocent people.<br>
<br>
Here's the absolute bottom line. Concepts such as Right and Wrong, Good and Evil don't really mean anything if you analyse them deeply enough. They're just abstractions built to try to enforce the prejudices of society's majorities.<br>
At some point we have to decide whether we're going to be honest about that. If we are, then we should firmly remove from our society anyone who doesn't think the same way we do[2]. If we're not, then the whole thing is a big waste of time and will continue to degenerate into a morass of confusion and over-legislation.<br>
<br>
Offensive, eh?<br>
Arryen / Ssetti<br>
<br>
